Area: City and Borough of Juneau
Description:
['Mendenhall Lake continues to rise this evening. Here is what we
know. Lake levels were steady around 7 ft, but began to rise
around 5 AM AKDT Sunday morning and are now approaching 8 ft.
Latest webcam image from Suicide Basin indicates that the basin is
still rising. This tells us that the most likely reason for the
rising lake level is due to runoff from heavy rainfall as well as
increased upper elevation ice melt.', 'With limited data to work with, initial estimates suggest that
the lake will continue to rise just above 8 ft before lowering
back below 8 ft early Monday morning. Continue to monitor
www.weather.gov/juneau for any additional updates.']

Description:
['* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.', '* WHERE...Cache River Near Patterson.', '* WHEN...Until further notice.', '* IMPACTS...At 10.0 feet, Pastureland and cropland not protected by
levees in Jackson and Woodruff counties affected. Water is over
portions of State Highway 37 and deep along the shoulders of State
Highway 18 near Grubbs. Water over portions of Woodruff County
Road 775 north of State Highway 260.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:15 PM CDT Sunday the stage was 9.9 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 10.0
feet early Tuesday morning.
- Flood stage is 9.0 feet.']

Description:

temperatures reaching up to 112 degrees and overnight lows as

risk.', '* WHERE...Shasta, Scott and Klamath River Valleys. The warmest
temperatures will be in the Klamath River Valley.', '* WHEN...From Sunday afternoon through Thursday afternoon.', '* IMPACTS...Hazardous heat will significantly increase the

outdoor activities without adequate hydration.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...If thunderstorms do form, then cloud cover

would reduce high temperatures and perhaps keep temperatures
warmer than anticipated overnight.', '* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr']

Description:
['The National Weather Service in Portland has issued a Red Flag
Warning for wind and low relative humidity, which is in effect
from 11 AM this morning to 11 PM PDT this evening.', '* AFFECTED AREA...In Oregon, Fire Weather Zone 601 North Oregon
Coast and Fire Weather Zone 602 North Oregon Coast Range. In
Washington, Fire Weather Zone 664 South Washington Coast and
West Willapa Hills and Fire Weather Zone 665 East Willapa
Hills.', '* WINDS...North to northeast 5 to 15 mph, with gusts up to 20
mph.', '* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...15 to 25 percent.', '* INSTABILITY...High haines (values of 5 to 6) indicate unstable
air mass, such that strong vertical motion could promote plume
dominated fire growth, with enhanced burning on any new fire
starts.', '* IMPACTS...Conditions may be favorable for rapid fire spread
which may threaten life and property. Use extra caution with
potential ignition sources, especially in grassy areas.']

Area: South  Willamette Valley; Cascade Foothills in Lane County; Cascades in Lane County
Description:
['The Lane Regional Air Protection Agency has issued an Air Quality
Advisory, which is in effect until 5 PM Tuesday afternoon.', 'An Air Quality Advisory for smoke has been issued. Wildfires burning
in the region combined with forecasted conditions will cause air
quality to reach unhealthy levels at times through Sunday.', 'Protect yourself and your family when smoke levels are high:', 'Stay inside if possible. Keep windows and doors closed. If its too
hot, run air conditioning on recirculate or consider moving to a
cooler location. Avoid strenuous outdoor activity. Use high-
efficiency particulate air (HEPA) filters in indoor ventilation
systems or portable air purifiers. Or create your own air purifying
filter by following these instructions. Be aware of smoke in your
area and avoid places with the highest levels. When air quality
improves to moderate or healthy (yellow or green on the Air Quality
Index), open windows and doors to air out homes and businesses. If
you have a breathing plan for a medical condition, be sure to follow
it and keep any needed medications refilled.', 'Cloth, dust and surgical masks dont protect from the harmful
particles in smoke. N95 or P100 respirators approved by NIOSH may
offer protection, but they must be properly selected and worn. Select
a NIOSH-approved respirator with a N, R or P alongside the number
95, 99 or 100. Learn how to put on and use a respirator. Respirators
wont work for children as they dont come in childrens sizes.
People with heart or lung conditions should consult their health care
provider before wearing a respirator.', 'More information about air quality can be found at:
www.lrapa.org']

heighten grass and wildfire risks.', 'All Southeast Texas counties have burn bans in effect. Avoid outdoor

sparks such as chains, bearings, exhaust and other equipment on
vehicles that could cause sparks. Avoid discarding lit cigarettes
